  "opinion": "As a delivery driver in New York with four kids and a PhD parent on one side, I’ve seen firsthand how science can feel out of reach for many. The gender gap in science isn’t just about numbers—it’s about who gets to dream big. My mom, who went to primary school, taught me to look at the world differently, and that’s what I try to pass on to my kids. I don’t think we should ignore the gap, but we shouldn’t fix it with the same old solutions. For instance, when I deliver packages to labs and schools, I notice how many girls are discouraged from STEM early on because they’re told it’s ‘not for them.’ But here’s the thing: science isn’t a solo act. It’s like birdwatching—each observation adds to the bigger picture. If we want to close the gap, we need to start in the community, not in classrooms. My kids love photography, and I’ve seen how creative play helps them see patterns. So, instead of pushing girls into labs, maybe we should create safe spaces where they can explore science through hobbies they already love. That way, the gap doesn’t feel like a barrier—it becomes part of the journey. I believe in addressing it, but not with top-down fixes. It’s about listening to the kids, the communities, and letting science be something everyone can touch.",
